- Exactly.

00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:56.190
I want to dispel the
notion that it's magical

00:12:56.190 --> 00:12:58.920
in that regard or that you have to fast.

00:12:58.920 --> 00:13:00.000
- Right, right.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.450
It's a, yeah, if you
prefer calorie deficit,

00:13:03.450 --> 00:13:06.363
you prefer a more normal every day,

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:09.881
which some people would.

00:13:09.881 --> 00:13:12.540
Especially like the dry fasting's great,

00:13:12.540 --> 00:13:15.060
but if you work outside in the heat,

00:13:15.060 --> 00:13:16.890
no, you cannot do dry fasting.

00:13:16.890 --> 00:13:19.047
Yeah that will not be prudent.

00:13:19.047 --> 00:13:20.820
- No, I tell everybody,

00:13:20.820 --> 00:13:25.620
if you even get hot at your
office, don't dry fast,

00:13:25.620 --> 00:13:29.280
you know, dry fast over the
weekends or something like that.

00:13:29.280 --> 00:13:31.833
There's a study, I'm sure
you've read this one,

00:13:35.190 --> 00:13:40.190
it was done in Germany by a
couple of Germans and Greeks.

00:13:40.230 --> 00:13:42.900
And the name's just not
coming to me right now,

00:13:42.900 --> 00:13:46.049
but it's a Greek name so
I'd probably ruin it anyway.

00:13:46.049 --> 00:13:50.610
But they did five day dry fasts.

00:13:50.610 --> 00:13:54.030
And there was a follow up
study where they replicated it.

00:13:54.030 --> 00:13:55.143
- That's a long fast.

00:13:56.490 --> 00:13:58.650
- Especially with no liquids.

00:13:58.650 --> 00:13:59.490
- Yeah.

00:13:59.490 --> 00:14:02.910
- And funny thing, like after a day,

00:14:02.910 --> 00:14:04.410
you just don't even think about it.

00:14:04.410 --> 00:14:05.913
I'm actually dry fasted,

00:14:07.290 --> 00:14:10.230
let's see, about 60 hours right now.

00:14:10.230 --> 00:14:11.063
- Really?

00:14:11.063 --> 00:14:11.896
Wow.

00:14:11.896 --> 00:14:12.750
- Yeah, I'm fine, I'm fine.

00:14:12.750 --> 00:14:15.510
And, you know, I noticed
little things like,

00:14:15.510 --> 00:14:18.030
you know, the level of hydration,

00:14:18.030 --> 00:14:21.180
like my hands don't look as
vascular as they normally do

00:14:21.180 --> 00:14:22.013
or whatever.

00:14:23.130 --> 00:14:26.910
But I did this the first time I did it,

00:14:26.910 --> 00:14:31.470
measured the volume of my urine each day,

00:14:31.470 --> 00:14:33.183
same amount of urine every day.

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:35.213
- Sorry?

00:14:35.213 --> 00:14:37.620
- Same amount of urine every day.

00:14:37.620 --> 00:14:39.300
- That's interesting, yeah.

00:14:39.300 --> 00:14:40.147
- Yeah.

00:14:40.147 --> 00:14:41.610
Well so then taking the water

00:14:41.610 --> 00:14:45.300
from our only nonvascular
tissue that we drag around,

00:14:45.300 --> 00:14:46.133
body fat.

00:14:47.160 --> 00:14:51.240
So it works really well.

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:54.900
But what I think the
mistake people are making

00:14:54.900 --> 00:14:57.600
is they're trying to
get away with tiny fasts

00:14:57.600 --> 00:14:59.430
that don't really do anything.

00:14:59.430 --> 00:15:01.440
And then they go and
eat too much. (laughs)

00:15:01.440 --> 00:15:03.600
So it's like, yeah.

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:06.540
I mean, if you're you're metabolic rate

00:15:06.540 --> 00:15:09.010
plus activities, like me, like 3,300

00:15:10.050 --> 00:15:13.083
and you just eat 3,300
calories at the end of the day,

00:15:14.174 --> 00:15:17.640
and you skip the first two
meals, like you did nothing.

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:19.500
- Yeah that's what most
people have with Ramadan

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:21.159
where they
- Yeah, oh and

00:15:21.159 --> 00:15:22.785
have all these treats
they eat like,

00:15:22.785 --> 00:15:23.618
and
feast at night

00:15:23.618 --> 00:15:24.840
and it's like, man.

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:26.760
- Yeah, most people end up maintaining,

00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:29.580
which is actually still surprising

00:15:29.580 --> 00:15:30.627
considering how much junk they eat

00:15:30.627 --> 00:15:33.543
and they still maintained
their body composition.

00:15:34.380 --> 00:15:35.213
- Right.

00:15:35.213 --> 00:15:37.590
Well, yeah,

00:15:37.590 --> 00:15:39.930
they only have a certain
window to be able to eat.

00:15:39.930 --> 00:15:41.042
So the sun has

00:15:41.042 --> 00:15:42.723
to be down.
- Yeah, exactly.

00:15:42.723 --> 00:15:45.300
They do a lot in short time.

00:15:45.300 --> 00:15:47.580
- Northern living Muslims,

00:15:47.580 --> 00:15:49.630
if you're a Muslim and you live in London

00:15:50.520 --> 00:15:52.920
your Ramadan day is quite a bit shorter

00:15:52.920 --> 00:15:54.990
than it is in the middle east.

00:15:54.990 --> 00:15:58.230
'Cause it's different,
hemisphere's different sunlight.

00:15:58.230 --> 00:16:01.440
And so they sometimes only
have like a couple hours to eat

00:16:01.440 --> 00:16:03.180
before they gotta go to bed

00:16:03.180 --> 00:16:05.070
and they're doing better

00:16:05.070 --> 00:16:06.840
because they don't have so much time

00:16:06.840 --> 00:16:08.280
to eat all the junk food

00:16:08.280 --> 00:16:10.480
they want to get in the
middle of the night.

00:16:11.460 --> 00:16:12.510
Yeah, I think that's-

00:16:13.920 --> 00:16:15.000
Well, I mean let's face it,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.220
they're not doing it for health.

00:16:17.220 --> 00:16:19.290
They're doing it for
the religious experience

00:16:19.290 --> 00:16:20.790
and you know, hey,

00:16:20.790 --> 00:16:23.010
they've given us more fasting data

00:16:23.010 --> 00:16:27.150
than anybody else 'cause it's
like 1 1/2 billion Muslims

00:16:27.150 --> 00:16:30.930
do it every year and people
aren't getting hurt by it.

00:16:30.930 --> 00:16:35.220
So I lean on that quite a bit.

00:16:35.220 --> 00:16:37.500
I got a lot of great references

00:16:37.500 --> 00:16:39.210
from some Middle Eastern journals.

00:16:39.210 --> 00:16:40.530
Now of course the Middle Eastern journals

00:16:40.530 --> 00:16:45.530
don't have the same standards
that the Western journals do,

00:16:45.840 --> 00:16:47.670
but they're getting better.

00:16:47.670 --> 00:16:48.720
And then every once in a while

00:16:48.720 --> 00:16:50.250
you see something in a Western journal,

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:51.390
you're like, wow,

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:53.440
who was on the peer review team for that?

00:16:55.484 --> 00:16:56.640
I ask myself
- Quite often.

00:16:56.640 --> 00:16:57.473
that question a lot.

00:16:57.473 --> 00:16:58.623
I'm sure you do too.

00:16:59.700 --> 00:17:00.533
- Yep.

00:17:00.533 --> 00:17:02.111
- Yeah, like some of the,

00:17:02.111 --> 00:17:04.380
have you noticed like how much,

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:05.400
it's 'cause of coronavirus,

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:09.570
but we have a lot more research
about just airborne viruses.

00:17:09.570 --> 00:17:11.430
And it's like,

00:17:11.430 --> 00:17:13.590
if you write a paper
about an airborne virus

00:17:13.590 --> 00:17:16.143
and you pick the wrong statistical test,

00:17:17.250 --> 00:17:18.570
I don't think anyone cares.

00:17:18.570 --> 00:17:21.900
It's getting published
because each journal

00:17:21.900 --> 00:17:25.140
wants the maximum amount
of content about that.

00:17:25.140 --> 00:17:28.023
And so the paper quality
has just gone down.

00:17:29.700 --> 00:17:31.590
Have you noticed that at all?

00:17:31.590 --> 00:17:32.423
Kinda?

00:17:32.423 --> 00:17:33.960
- I'm not an expert on viruses,

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:36.100
but I do notice-

00:17:36.100 --> 00:17:37.530
A main thing I noticed

00:17:37.530 --> 00:17:41.040
is that there was a big slump in research.

00:17:41.040 --> 00:17:46.040
I mean my own paper that
was almost finished,

00:17:46.080 --> 00:17:49.080
we are actually doing a study
on faster training and fasting

00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:53.490
as well with Andie Galpin

00:17:53.490 --> 00:17:55.860
and the last cohort

00:17:55.860 --> 00:17:59.580
was like in the last weeks of being done

00:17:59.580 --> 00:18:01.800
and then the Corona pandemic hit,

00:18:01.800 --> 00:18:03.540
and the lockdowns, and everything

00:18:03.540 --> 00:18:04.710
and it completely messed it up,

00:18:04.710 --> 00:18:05.970
completely confounded everything

00:18:05.970 --> 00:18:07.740
because everyone couldn't train anymore,

00:18:07.740 --> 00:18:09.810
their whole schedules changed.

00:18:09.810 --> 00:18:12.960
So now we're still trying
to rerun that cohort.

00:18:12.960 --> 00:18:15.240
So that completely messed up our study.

00:18:15.240 --> 00:18:17.250
And I know from a lot of
people that's happened.

00:18:17.250 --> 00:18:19.710
So there's also been actually the downside

00:18:19.710 --> 00:18:21.627
that is often not
discussed of the pandemic

00:18:21.627 --> 00:18:24.960
and the lockdowns is the
damage it did to research

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:28.110
'cause it messed up so much research.

00:18:28.110 --> 00:18:28.943
- Sure.

00:18:28.943 --> 00:18:30.690
Oh, anything that was at a university

00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:33.510
now all of a sudden people
can't go to the university.

00:18:33.510 --> 00:18:34.343
- Yep.
- Yeah,

00:18:34.343 --> 00:18:35.730
I had that challenge also.

00:18:35.730 --> 00:18:38.063
There's a couple things that
I'm trying to have done.

00:18:39.189 --> 00:18:40.788
When they close the university

00:18:40.788 --> 00:18:45.788
it's never like the sports
performance department,

00:18:48.840 --> 00:18:52.253
the nutrition department,
the endocrinology department,

00:18:52.253 --> 00:18:54.720
they don't call and say,
yeah, I don't do that.

00:18:54.720 --> 00:18:56.070
They just have to do it.

00:18:56.070 --> 00:19:00.930
So yeah, that was annoying.

00:19:00.930 --> 00:19:04.310
Well now have you been in
Portugal the entire time

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:06.180
during coronavirus?

00:19:06.180 --> 00:19:07.410
- No, no.

00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:10.860
Mostly in Brazil and Mexico,

00:19:10.860 --> 00:19:13.473
but I have had four lockdowns
in various countries.

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:16.253
- Yeah.

00:19:18.135 --> 00:19:19.333
We won't talk about the-
- I think it's on the way out.

00:19:19.333 --> 00:19:22.503
- We won't talk about the
research on lockdowns.

00:19:27.099 --> 00:19:30.750
When you finish that meta-analysis,

00:19:30.750 --> 00:19:32.193
or the systematic review,

00:19:34.470 --> 00:19:37.443
was there anything that you
wished you had got in there,

00:19:38.850 --> 00:19:41.700
I mean like you said, there are no metrics

00:19:41.700 --> 00:19:45.060
on what the calorie controls were.

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:48.660
And so like that's like
gigantic question mark,

00:19:48.660 --> 00:19:51.120
but I mean you couldn't
do anything about it.

00:19:51.120 --> 00:19:52.140
- Yeah, I mean,

00:19:52.140 --> 00:19:55.182
I think the fact that
it's still overwhelmingly

00:19:55.182 --> 00:19:57.420
in favor against carbs.

00:19:57.420 --> 00:19:59.340
So no matter how you look at the research,

00:19:59.340 --> 00:20:01.890
no matter which category we
looked at, which timeframe,

00:20:01.890 --> 00:20:04.320
the majority of studies
found no beneficial effects

00:20:04.320 --> 00:20:06.810
on higher carbo intakes.

00:20:06.810 --> 00:20:09.180
And then you're looking at few categories

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:12.957
where I think there could be
an actual influence of carbs,

00:20:12.957 --> 00:20:15.900
not just a psychological
one, but an actual one.

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:19.530
And that's basically people
that train twice a day,

00:20:19.530 --> 00:20:22.203
athletes that do endurance
and strength training,

00:20:23.820 --> 00:20:25.380
people that do more than 10 sets

00:20:25.380 --> 00:20:26.820
per muscle group per session,

00:20:26.820 --> 00:20:27.653
which is interesting,

00:20:27.653 --> 00:20:30.030
if you do like the more
broken up kind of workouts,

00:20:30.030 --> 00:20:30.863
old schools,

00:20:32.010 --> 00:20:35.130
then actually you might
need the carbs a little bit.

00:20:35.130 --> 00:20:36.000
It's not a big difference,

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:38.463
but it might have an effect.

00:20:39.360 --> 00:20:42.510
Again, though in the only
calorie control study

00:20:42.510 --> 00:20:43.530
by (indistinct)

00:20:43.530 --> 00:20:45.840
they found no effect even up to 15 sets

00:20:45.840 --> 00:20:46.890
for one muscle group.

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:52.800
But it's not a category I'm
particularly interested in

00:20:52.800 --> 00:20:54.480
because I'm generally a proponent

00:20:54.480 --> 00:20:55.950
of higher frequency training.

00:20:55.950 --> 00:20:57.219
- Yeah, me neither.

00:20:57.219 --> 00:20:59.430
(men speak over each other)

00:20:59.430 --> 00:21:00.870
and you let it recover.

00:21:00.870 --> 00:21:04.800
- Yeah I don't have my
clients do like 15 plus sets

00:21:04.800 --> 00:21:06.600
per muscle group per session anyway.

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:11.827
- Yeah, that's even
higher volume than I go.

00:21:11.827 --> 00:21:13.683
More than that we talk about.

00:21:16.240 --> 00:21:20.703
So like someone wants
to be low carbohydrate,

00:21:23.430 --> 00:21:28.233
they do 20 minute weight
workout, six days a week.

00:21:31.050 --> 00:21:33.090
You talk about replenishing glycogen

00:21:33.090 --> 00:21:35.520
in pretty much the first,

00:21:35.520 --> 00:21:40.520
I think you mentioned like
15 grams of let's say glucose

00:21:41.700 --> 00:21:44.823
or a carbohydrate's gonna
convert into glucose,

00:21:47.490 --> 00:21:50.613
you're really kind of there.

00:21:51.817 --> 00:21:53.373
Is that correct?

00:21:54.388 --> 00:21:55.650
- Yeah, I think so

00:21:55.650 --> 00:21:58.980
because we have three direct studies

00:21:58.980 --> 00:22:00.690
on sort of the dose response

00:22:00.690 --> 00:22:02.493
and overall in the literature,

00:22:03.570 --> 00:22:06.240
it's very clear there's
no dose response effects.

00:22:06.240 --> 00:22:08.070
Which is a big red flag, right?

00:22:08.070 --> 00:22:10.500
The idea is that you
need the carbs for energy

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:13.950
and therefore you would expect
that the more carbs you need,

00:22:13.950 --> 00:22:14.850
the more energy you have,

00:22:14.850 --> 00:22:17.070
thus the better you perform.

00:22:17.070 --> 00:22:18.810
But it doesn't pan out that way at all.

00:22:18.810 --> 00:22:21.660
Like there is no dose
response effects in literature

00:22:21.660 --> 00:22:23.010
and it's because you typically

00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:26.220
just don't deplete enough
glycogen during your workouts.

00:22:26.220 --> 00:22:29.070
The highest reported value
in the entire literature,

00:22:29.070 --> 00:22:31.973
and there's a lot of papers, is 41%.

00:22:32.880 --> 00:22:36.930
And so in one session you're almost never

00:22:36.930 --> 00:22:38.220
gonna burn for all of your glycogen.

00:22:38.220 --> 00:22:42.810
Now maybe if you're going
into the 15 plus set range,

00:22:42.810 --> 00:22:45.390
then you might deplete
glycogen levels enough

00:22:45.390 --> 00:22:48.120
in some of your type two muscle fibers,

00:22:48.120 --> 00:22:49.950
but again, I think that's not a category

00:22:49.950 --> 00:22:51.450
people should train in anyway.

00:22:53.610 --> 00:22:55.530
It's not super practical.

00:22:55.530 --> 00:22:57.270
And then afterwards,

00:22:57.270 --> 00:22:59.790
if you look at the values
of glycogen resynthesis,

00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:03.720
which can occur from the glycerol
backbone of triglycerides

00:23:03.720 --> 00:23:05.490
or via a Cori cycle

00:23:05.490 --> 00:23:08.970
where the lactates, the pump
that you get in workouts,

00:23:08.970 --> 00:23:10.470
there's a lot of lactate production.

00:23:10.470 --> 00:23:13.170
It can effectively be
recycled back to glucose.

00:23:13.170 --> 00:23:15.480
So the body has very
effective mechanisms in place

00:23:15.480 --> 00:23:18.780
to resynthesize glycogen
without actually needing

00:23:18.780 --> 00:23:20.760
dietary carbohydrates.

00:23:20.760 --> 00:23:22.500
And then if you look at the levels

00:23:22.500 --> 00:23:24.750
that glycogen resynthesis occurs

00:23:24.750 --> 00:23:27.783
in people that are even
fasted, like completely fasted,

00:23:29.010 --> 00:23:30.570
it's still within the range where you say,

00:23:30.570 --> 00:23:32.070
oh, look after a normal workout,

00:23:32.070 --> 00:23:34.680
this would take about 24 hours to recover.

00:23:34.680 --> 00:23:36.540
So even if you're training
them also every day,

00:23:36.540 --> 00:23:38.943
which I do in some high
frequency programs,

00:23:39.889 --> 00:23:42.447
they show complete resynthesis.

00:23:42.447 --> 00:23:44.220
And that's why if you look at the studies,

00:23:44.220 --> 00:23:45.690
the longer term studies,

00:23:45.690 --> 00:23:47.550
actually the evidence became
more and more convincing.

00:23:47.550 --> 00:23:49.737
Like the longer the timeframe you look at

00:23:49.737 --> 00:23:52.800
in research studies, the
more convincing the evidence

00:23:52.800 --> 00:23:55.050
that there's no effect whatsoever.

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:56.729
I think in our long term category

00:23:56.729 --> 00:23:58.596
of studies up to three months,

00:23:58.596 --> 00:24:01.830
which is about as long as
most of these studies go

00:24:01.830 --> 00:24:04.440
'cause you typically have
college athletes and whatever,

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:09.060
it's I think it was 17
studies, 15 found no benefit.

00:24:09.060 --> 00:24:10.680
And then it was actually one to one,

00:24:10.680 --> 00:24:11.997
one found the benefits of higher carbs

00:24:11.997 --> 00:24:14.100
and one actually favored lower carbs,

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:17.850
so cancel that out, it's
basically a complete wash,

00:24:17.850 --> 00:24:21.843
like no evidence for in favor
of higher carbohydrates.

00:24:22.831 --> 00:24:25.920
- Man, I know, (coughs)

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:28.653
Sorry, I have a little
allergy problem here.

00:24:29.730 --> 00:24:30.750
I live in California,

00:24:30.750 --> 00:24:33.453
we get a lot of plants and
they make a lot of pollen.

00:24:35.760 --> 00:24:40.760
So God, that's such a breath of fresh air

00:24:41.760 --> 00:24:45.720
because so many people who,

00:24:45.720 --> 00:24:50.603
I mean, really, they just want
to eat candy, like whatever.

00:24:52.230 --> 00:24:54.930
Like all the time somebody will,

00:24:54.930 --> 00:24:55.950
just this morning,

00:24:55.950 --> 00:25:00.950
somebody posted on our forum,
the X3 Users Group forum,

00:25:01.440 --> 00:25:03.693
they posted some about like donuts.

00:25:04.680 --> 00:25:07.381
Like last thing I would eat.

00:25:07.381 --> 00:25:08.214
What?

00:25:09.564 --> 00:25:12.000
And the problem with a donut isn't just,

00:25:12.000 --> 00:25:13.350
if you want to have a one donut,

00:25:13.350 --> 00:25:14.730
can you have one donut?

00:25:14.730 --> 00:25:15.720
I suppose,

00:25:15.720 --> 00:25:20.640
but then you're gonna want
to eat the rest of them too.

00:25:20.640 --> 00:25:22.620
You're not gonna want to eat one.

00:25:22.620 --> 00:25:24.962
And it just switches

00:25:24.962 --> 00:25:28.443
your insulin on,
- That's good, yeah.

00:25:28.443 --> 00:25:32.250
in a way that's so up regulated so quickly

00:25:32.250 --> 00:25:33.720
that you lose control

00:25:33.720 --> 00:25:34.560
and that's when people

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:35.994
really fall, right?

00:25:35.994 --> 00:25:36.827
- Yeah, that's exactly

00:25:36.827 --> 00:25:37.890
