00:25:37.890 --> 00:25:40.740
where people think they have a very naive

00:25:40.740 --> 00:25:42.150
notional food cravings,

00:25:42.150 --> 00:25:44.520
where they feel like if
you eat a little bit,

00:25:44.520 --> 00:25:45.840
the craving's gone.

00:25:45.840 --> 00:25:47.460
But actually it's the opposite.

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:49.860
The best way to kill a
craving is to starve it.

00:25:49.860 --> 00:25:51.270
Like you don't eat something

00:25:51.270 --> 00:25:52.500
and then the craving disappears

00:25:52.500 --> 00:25:54.600
and research is super,
super clear on this.

00:25:54.600 --> 00:25:56.280
That people that need
low carb, for example,

00:25:56.280 --> 00:25:57.900
they lose their carb cravings,

00:25:57.900 --> 00:25:59.550
'cause they never eat them.

00:25:59.550 --> 00:26:01.350
Whereas if you eat a carb,

00:26:01.350 --> 00:26:02.640
it doesn't matter how much you eat,

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:04.140
that's another interesting finding.

00:26:04.140 --> 00:26:06.240
If you eat one donut or you eat 10 donuts,

00:26:06.240 --> 00:26:09.480
the increasing cravings for
donuts is actually the same

00:26:09.480 --> 00:26:11.430
because it's not about
the physical process

00:26:11.430 --> 00:26:13.590
